post_text:
Final reminder....Freshmen Transition Camp for incoming freshmen will take place on Wednesday, August 5, 2020 and Thursday August 6, 2020 from 11:00am to 2:00pm. This is a program that has been implemented at the high school to ease the incoming student's transition to high school. The program will be virtual and synchronous meaning that the students will be interacting with each other and our Kingsway ambassadors. During this two day program there will be scheduled activities to build positive relationships, ease anxiety and cultivate dragon pride. There will be activities designed around digital citizenship, goal setting, peer pressure, conflict resolution and emotion regulation.

If interested please register at the link below and a zoom link will be sent to you. https://forms.gle/qwt7B3xUHpenwQzU6

post_text: Congratulations to our KRHS Dragons who participated in the USA Biolympiad Club (USABO) this year. Students spent the year working with Mrs. Ninan preparing for the USABO exam. Officers got a chance to teach, to lead and to have meaningful dialogue with the club members. Kingsway was the only school in South Jersey to participate! Here are all the students that participated: Alexandra Pechlivanidis, Ananya Raghavan, Angelique Girard, Briana Worrell, Cole Griscom, Elise Poling, Esha Shinh, Ishareet Sohal, Jessica Zhang, Katarina Leisinger, Laken Franchetti, Madison Phun ,Max M, Nikolaos Kalfas, Nora Beebe, Olivia Smith, Paige Gould, Patricia Martin, Rabiya Haque, Seth Sims, & Timothy Ninan.

This Monday we begin celebrating Faculty & Staff Appreciation Week. While we cannot thank our teachers, paraprofessionals, secretaries, transportation staff, custodians, maintenance and grounds personnel, technology and food service staff, and district personnel in person, we appreciate each and every one of them for their tireless commitment to our students. Our administrative team has put together a few creative ways to say ‚Äòthank you‚Äô for the critical role each employee plays in our district, including a Virtual Wellness Week for all of our employees to provide daily self-care activities to help them relax and have fun.

Parents, students and alumni are encouraged to send a faculty or a staff member a note of appreciation.

Please take a moment to review a number of updates at the link below regarding our Virtual Learning Program, upcoming events, and more. April‚Äôs Board Brief and 2020-21 Budget Narrative can be found here as well.

April 3, 2020

Dear Parents, Students & School Community,

I wanted to take a moment to provide our parents, students and school community a quick update regarding a number of topics before we break for spring recess. I am sure you agree that these past few weeks have been exhausting and the welcomed reprieve from virtual schooling could not be timelier. I have encouraged our faculty and staff to enjoy the recess and to disengage from the computer. I am also encouraging our students to do the same, as this is an opportunity to for us all to catch our breath, enjoy some fresh air ‚Äì while practicing social distancing ‚Äì and engage in fulfilling activities.

We end this week on a high note and I share with you some feel-good highlights and my student message by below.

Dear Parents, Students & School Community,

Now that we have started our third week of the Virtual Learning Program, and this week‚Äôs Virtual Spirit Week, I wanted to share a number of critical updates with our parents, guardians and students so that we are all prepared for the days and weeks ahead. This update also serves as a moment to stress the importance of continuing our social distancing practices, especially among our students, as our best strategy in flattening the proverbial curve.

I wish each of you continued success while we navigate these unprecedented times and hope that this update serves you well as we continue to work hard at providing our students with the very best program possible. Should you have any questions, please do not hesitate to reach out to me at your convenience.

Click the link below for important updates.

Stay home, healthy & happy!
James Lavender

I‚Äôm so proud to be Kingsway & South Harrison‚Äôs Superintendent of Schools and of our Board leadership team, administrators, teachers and support staff. This special group of educators came together to address an unprecedented crisis and developed a viable and sustainable plan to deliver virtual instruction to all of our students, deploy Chromebooks to those who needed them and began providing lunches to our neediest students. We worked around the clock and overcame adversity, together!!! As a member of our community it‚Äôs heartwarming to know that we stood tall when the stakes were high. While there will be more to communicate, please know I‚Äôm overwhelmed with appreciation and admiration for my colleagues, parents and students. Be safe everyone!

Kingsway Regional Performing Arts invites you to our creepy, kooky, mysterious, and spooky production of The Addams Family next month!

Performances are March 12th, 13th, and 14th at 6:30pm with an additional matinee on March 14th at 1:00 in the Eitel Theatre at Kingsway Regional High School. Tickets are $10 for everyone and will be available both through pre-order (using the form below) and at the door. The lobby and theatre open half an hour before the start time, so get in early to get the best seats as well as refreshments!

If you would like to pre-order tickets, please use the following form: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSe5gaXR8nF_RiAv6ECIJtSjVsD4JoKI7dfDNh5Bb10enStL1w/viewform. For any questions regarding ticketing, please contact Sarah Reynolds at reynoldss@krsd.org.
NOTE: This form only allows you to reserve tickets, not pay for them. You will need to pay at will call when you pick up your tickets the night of the show. Tickets are $10 each.

We hope to see you snapping along with our incredible team soon!

post_text: Kingsway Regional School District will again be offering select AP mock test sessions for interested students enrolled in AP classes at Kingsway. During this time, students will take part in a simulated exam facilitated by Kingsway teachers (about 3 hours) with a debrief session to follow (about 1 hour). The purpose of these sessions is to familiarize students with the AP exam prior to the May 4th ‚Äì 15th administration in an effort to secure confidence and to identify areas to focus on prior to the actual assessment. Students interested in the scheduled AP Mock Test Sessions can sign up via the link provided by March 13, 2020. Students must use their Kingsway Gmail account to access the form to sign up. https://forms.gle/F7XmmDWoSy54WcyZ6

post_text: On February 13th, Kingsway hosted William Green from The Youth Alliance as a speaker for all of our High School Students. Willie‚Äôs message highlights resilience through any situation, no matter how difficult it may be. He encouraged Kingsway students to keep moving forward and encouraged them to reach out for help and support. William grew up in Atlantic City, NJ and faced difficult times. He did not always have a positive attitude about his situation and used alcohol and drugs to try and fill his pain. Support from others helped him to change his mind set and set goals for himself. Through hard work and determination, he played football in college and went on to be a first round draft pick in the NFL. Despite his struggles early on in life, he kept pushing forward and found success. ‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt have to be great to get started. You just have to get started to be great.‚Äù

The three day festival invites bands from around the region to perform for the jazz faculty and takes part in hands on instruction from the area's top jazz musicians.
